{
  "name": "svbi-apple-xserve-kastner-2002-05-17-1398db",
  "title": "Apple server piques interest of Mac shops (Silicon Valley Business Ink, May 17, 2002)",
  "description": "Silicon Valley Business Ink (May 17, 2002) reports on Apple Computer's May 14, 2002 launch of the rack-mounted Xserve server, positioned against revamped G4s and iMacs used as servers in offices and schools. Entry model: single-G4 processor, $2,999; two-processor: $3,999. Quotes Dean Nelson (Allegro Networks test engineer running 184 G4s and 23 racks \u2014 'I could literally put that in four racks [of the new Apple servers]'), Mike Hathaway (Fremont Union HS adult education, excited about redundancy), Tim Deal (Technology Business Research \u2014 'historical moment for this incarnation of Apple'), Steve Jobs ('we're approaching this very carefully and have a lot to learn'), and Peter Kastner (Aberdeen Group Chief Research Officer): Kastner 'likes the price and the technology, but isn't confident Apple can dent the enterprise server market. It's too late for Apple to get back into the bread-and-butter enterprise market for desktops and servers.' Mentions Genentech purchasing 1,000 iMacs for staff.",
